<br>
What does it take to keep your house (guild) in order?<br>
<br>
Even though Mistaken Identity is very young (Formed in August of '01) We've been picky as can be with who is invited and had few if any real problems.<br>
<br>
Yes, there is the constant issue of maintaining focus, but we've addressed that by staying small. MI will never go over roughly 80 people. We won't go to a lot of places by ourselves, but the style, quality and temperment of our members will get us invited along on larger raids more often than not.<br>
<br>
So as leaders, officers, and members, what do you think it takes to not only avoid disbandment, but keep the game fun as a guild?<br>
<br>
/salute Clan Skallagrim<br>
/salute Arcane Asylium <p><img src="http://www.mistakenid.org/images/aspsig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/ulernz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LernZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sissy Wizzy</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/22/02 10:48:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3097.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Keep Your House in Order?</span><hr size=1> a) Strong officers that can help push the guild in the &quot;right&quot; direction (insert your guilds objectives here), but remain flexible and open to input from the guild.  CiH is very flexible.  While I personally as an officer would love to say, no more raiding in Velious other then tunare and AoW, the guild on a whole feels differently.  I have to do whats best for the guild, not whats best for me.<br>
<br>
b) Members willingness to follow the leaders<br>
<br>
c) Members willingness to get along with each other<br>
<br>
d) Setting reasonable goals for the guild.  Failure to have reasonable goals just adds to the stress of members.  Small baby steps of progress keep a lot of people happy, vs wipeouts every night trying to do a mob your just not rdy for.<br>
<br>
e) Members with similar play styles helps.  It doesnt do any good if half your guild power games, is lvl 60, has tons of AA points etc, while the other half log in once or twice a week.  Your guild will be split in half between those that want to advance faster then the other half. <p><center>
